        width="600"
        height="450"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg w-full"
      />
    </div>
    <div>
  <p>
    A WVO centrifuge operates as a <strong>3-phase, self-cleaning disc stack separator</strong>. The centrifuge bowl spins at high speed, generating up to <strong>8,000 Gs</strong> of centrifugal force. This extreme force separates the oil, water, and solids based on their density differences &mdash; a process that takes seconds rather than the hours required for gravity settling.
  </p>

  <p>
    The three phases are separated simultaneously:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Clean oil (light phase):</strong> Purified WVO migrates toward the center of the rotating bowl and exits through the light-phase outlet</li>
    <li><strong>Water (heavy phase):</strong> Water and water-soluble contaminants are forced outward by centrifugal force and exit through the heavy-phase discharge</li>
    <li><strong>Sludge (solids):</strong> Solid particles accumulate at the bowl periphery and are periodically ejected through hydraulically operated discharge ports</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    The self-cleaning mechanism is critical for WVO processing. The centrifuge bowl contains a <strong>sludge space</strong> at its periphery where solids accumulate during operation. At timed intervals, the bowl opens momentarily to eject the collected sludge, then closes and resumes separation &mdash; all without stopping the flow of oil. This enables <strong>continuous, unattended operation</strong> for extended production runs.
  </p>

  <p>
    Separation efficiency reaches down to <strong>1 micron for solids</strong> and <strong>2 microns for water droplets</strong>, far surpassing what conventional filters or gravity settling can achieve. The disc stack inside the bowl creates hundreds of thin separation channels, dramatically increasing the effective settling area within a compact footprint.
  </p>
    </div>
  </div>

