  <h3>Collection &amp; Pre-Treatment</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Collection tank:</strong> Incoming WVO is received and stored in a heated collection tank. Heating to 140&ndash;180&deg;F reduces viscosity and promotes initial gravity separation of free water and heavy sediment.</li>
    <li><strong>Feed pump:</strong> A positive displacement pump delivers WVO from the collection tank to the processing line at a controlled, consistent flow rate.</li>
    <li><strong>Strainer:</strong> An inline basket strainer (typically 100&ndash;200 mesh) removes large debris &mdash; food particles, plastic fragments, and other foreign objects &mdash; that could damage downstream equipment.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>De-Sludging (Decanter Stage)</h3>
  <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-6 items-start mb-6">
    <div class="md:w-[40%] shrink-0">
      <img
        src="/images/wvo-centrifuge-separator/Alfa-Laval-Decanter-for-WVO-De-Sludging-1000.webp"
        alt="Alfa Laval Decanter for WVO De-Sludging"
        width="600"
        height="450"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg w-full"
      />
    </div>
    <div>
  <p>
    For WVO with high solids content (particularly grease trap waste), an <strong><a href="/alfa-laval-nx-314-decanter-centrifuge/">NX-314 decanter centrifuge</a></strong> is used as a first-stage de-sludging unit. The decanter removes heavy sludge and large solids that would otherwise overload the disc stack centrifuge sludge space. This extends the interval between disc centrifuge sludge ejections and improves overall system efficiency.
  </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Heating &amp; Conditioning</h3>
  <ol start="4">
    <li><strong>Heat exchanger:</strong> A plate or shell-and-tube heat exchanger brings the oil to optimal processing temperature (typically 180&deg;F). Proper temperature is critical for reducing viscosity and achieving rated centrifuge capacity.</li>
    <li><strong>3-way valve:</strong> A diverter valve allows the operator to recirculate oil back to the collection tank if quality targets are not met, or to direct flow forward to the centrifuge.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Centrifugal Separation</h3>
  <ol start="6">
    <li><strong>Disc stack centrifuge:</strong> The self-cleaning disc centrifuge performs the primary 3-phase separation, producing clean oil, separated water, and ejected sludge as distinct output streams.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Output Streams</h3>
  <ol start="7">
    <li><strong>Clean oil tank:</strong> Purified WVO is collected for sale or further processing (e.g., <a href="/biodiesel-centrifuge/">biodiesel production</a>)</li>
    <li><strong>Water tank:</strong> Separated water is collected for disposal or treatment</li>
    <li><strong>Sludge tank:</strong> Ejected sludge is collected for disposal or rendering</li>
  </ol>

  <blockquote>
    For high-volume operations processing grease trap waste, the combination of an NX-314 decanter for de-sludging and a DMPX-042 disc stack centrifuge for final purification provides the highest throughput and cleanest output quality.
  </blockquote>

